When the 'prompt()' function is called, it displays a dialog box with the specified message as a prompt to the user. The function then waits for the user to enter a value and click either the 'OK' or 'Cancel' button.

If the user clicks 'OK' and provides an input value, the function returns the value entered as a string. If the user clicks 'Cancel' or closes the dialog box, the function returns 'null'.

Here's an example of how to use the 'prompt()' function in JavaScript:

```javascript
var userInput = prompt('Please enter your name:');

if (userInput !== null) {
  console.log('Hello, ' + userInput + '!');
} else {
  console.log('User cancelled the prompt dialog.');
}
```

